`inline` has a different meaning in C++. The compiler is free to inline the call if it wishes to, but `inline` means that the same function can be defined in multiple translation units without breaking the one definition rule. Example:<p><pre><code>    // header.hpp
    inline int f(int x) { return x + 1; }

    // a.cpp
    #include &quot;header.hpp&quot;

    // b.cpp
    #include &quot;header.hpp&quot;
</code></pre>
If f was not marked inline, linking a.cpp and b.cpp together would find a conflicting method f, and compilation would fail. `inline` lets the compiler ignore this, and it simply picks one of the multiple definitions as the &#x27;real&#x27; one and moves on with the compilation.
